{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13992"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13992"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.18,0.38,0.15,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41180"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"6399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17105"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the Paediatric Emergency Department with a five-and-a-half-hour history of acute left scrotal pain and swelling. He also reports nausea and has vomited once. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His observations are normal, and he is afebrile. The left hemiscrotum is swollen and exquisitely tender to palpation. The left testicle is positioned higher than the right and the cremasteric reflex is absent on the left side. Urgent surgical exploration confirms testicular torsion and reveals an underlying anatomical variation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the likely anatomical abnormality found?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incomplete descent of the testicle","Abnormal attachment of the epididymis","Complete encapsulation of testicle and cord by tunica vaginalis","Adherence of tunica vaginalis to scrotal wall","Absence of the gubernaculum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anatomical abnormality most likely found in this case is the bellclapper deformity, characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete encapsulation of testicle and cord by tunica vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E. In normal anatomy, the tunica vaginalis only partially covers the testicle, anchoring it posteriorly to the scrotum. In the bellclapper deformity, however, the tunica vaginalis completely envelops both the testicle and a portion of the spermatic cord. This arrangement allows the testicle to rotate freely within the tunica vaginalis, similar to a clapper in a bell, predisposing it to torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete descent of the testicle\u003C/strong\u003E (cryptorchidism) is a risk factor for torsion but is distinct from the bellclapper deformity. While it can increase torsion risk, it does so through different mechanisms and would have been noted on initial examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal attachment of the epididymis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to various epididymal anomalies unrelated to the bellclapper deformity. While these can affect testicular function, they do not typically increase torsion risk in the same manner as the bellclapper anomaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdherence of tunica vaginalis to scrotal wall\u003C/strong\u003E would actually prevent testicular torsion by restricting testicular movement. This is contrary to the bellclapper deformity, where excessive mobility is the key issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence of the gubernaculum\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of the bellclapper deformity. The gubernaculum plays a role in testicular descent during fetal development, but its absence is not directly linked to the increased torsion risk seen in the bellclapper anomaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the bellclapper deformity is crucial in managing testicular torsion. This anatomical variation often affects both testes, which is why surgeons typically perform bilateral orchiopexy during surgical exploration for torsion. This procedure fixes both testicles to the scrotal wall, preventing future torsion events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is typical for testicular torsion: sudden-onset scrotal pain, nausea and vomiting, and examination findings of a swollen, tender, high-riding testicle with absent cremasteric reflex. These features, combined with the short duration of symptoms, underscore the need for urgent surgical exploration in suspected cases of testicular torsion to maximise the chance of testicular salvage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testicular torsion is a surgical emergency requiring immediate intervention.","The bellclapper deformity, characterised by excessive testicular mobility due to complete encapsulation by the tunica vaginalis, is a common predisposing factor for torsion.","Bilateral orchiopexy is recommended during surgical exploration for torsion to prevent future torsion events in both testes."],"references":["Steinhardt GF, Hensle TW. Causes of scrotal pain in children and adolescents. In: UpToDate [online]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/causes-of-scrotal-pain-in-children-and-adolescents"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41180"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13992"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41180"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T10:22:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T10:23:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m